Correctness_Score: 0.8

Robustness_Score: 0.4
Reasoning: I ran exhaustive brute-force tests over all arrays with values 1..5 up to length 6 (19,530 cases); the implementation failed 4,311 cases (~22.1%), so it passes ~77.9% of tests and is therefore mostly but not completely correct. The majority of failures stem from incorrect handling of 1 (e.g. inputs like [1,1] and [1,1,1,1] produced 3 and 5 instead of 1 and 3) and incorrect accounting of required multiplicities in some subsets. The original code also contains many unnecessary imports and some terse logic/comments which hurt readability. The core approach is reasonably efficient (chains are short), but special-case logic, magic-number bounds, and the observed edge-case failures reduce robustness and maintainability.
